content.description: Fantastic route with good movement and flow. Nice degree of overhang leads to a bulge at the top.  Bottom and upper cruxes are separated by a great rest just under the 4th bolt. Good footwork will get you through the upper crux.
content.protection: 4 bolts and sport clips at the chains
content.location: Undead Cats wall to the left of the large roof

content.description: Start on the obvious nose shaped tufa (the schnoz). First deadpoint move getting from the tufa to a right hand ledge is the crux. Pretty straight forward from there to the chains. This is an enjoyable route, but I've seen a decent amount of people struggle with the start.

Real cool route. Crux might be between 2nd and 3rd bolts. Route starts going up, then meanders right before finishing back upwards. 

  Good if you like crimps and pockets.
content.location:
Towards the right end of Undead Cats wall, a couple of routes right of the nose shaped tufa.  

  Look for a small circle pocket around bolt 3 and a larger soft-ball sized pocket towards the top. That's your line.

content.description: May be harder than 5.11b.
Start left of Nac Nac, first bolt surrounded on two sides by a square shaped flake/undercling combo. Big moves to the 3rd bolt, followed by easier climbing to the lip.
content.location: Left side of undead cats wall at the far left side of the big roof

content.description: Like most Rupesh routes, this one feels harder than those of the same grade nearby. Powerful moves pulling the first lip yields to decent holds below the second lip. Figure out how to get to the jug over the 2nd roof, then dont be too pumped to pull on a few more bad holds before jugs to the chains.
content.location: Left of Rushin Brunette, just right of Werecats.

content.description: Obvious line through the center of the huge roof. Crux is from the last bolt out to the chains.
Short route with fun, powerful moves that culminate in an enigmatic anchoring stance. Be careful with the holds in the middle as they are a bit crumbly.Â
content.location: Located on the rightmost side of Undead Cats Wall. Shares a start with the route My Name Was Muffin (that splits off to right). Starts/belays from on top of the large rock beneath the route.

content.description: This was Kirk's last route. It is left of Unfinished Monkey Business. High Bolt 1 is left of the mini arete-dihedral pair. Bolt 3 is left of the wide "V" crack at the top of the cliff. Rope drag on lowering can get you stuck. To prevent that, clip anchors left-to-right, then separate the rope ends before lowering.

Start under a rectangular block located above bolt #1. Break out some sweet toe hook beta to pull the initial roof. Decent size holds trending up and left serve up a nice pump and lead you to the chains. The guide book suggest a grade of 5.11c, but the boulder problem pulling the initial roof merits 5.11d in my opinion.
content.protection: 4 bolts plus chains. Bolt #4 and chains are shared by Rushin Brunette. At the time of the writing, there were aluminum biners on the chains

content.description: So much fun packed into a short route. Gain the face with powerful or static beta and enter a world of balance under the crux bulge. The wave shaped face at the 3rd bolt will test your clipping skills. Finger pockets over the bulge will test your tendons and pulling power.

Variation of Unfinished Monkey Business. After bolt 3 head up and right to the ledge and traverse it to the right, clipping 3 more bolts to finish on the anchors of My Name Was Muffin.

 To clean have someone follow on backrope or else downclimb.
No comment
Fun route using good, positive pockets.
This route involves big moves from both sharp and rounded crimps.
content.location: You'll notice  a grey hueco around chest level and  decent side pulls a few feet to the right.

content.description: Shares a start with Lessamir and branches up and right. Superb movement right off the deck with a V4 boulder problem to a HUGE resting just. Two more moves lead you into a shallow 2 finger right hand pocket just below the 4th bolt. Pull the bulge and clip the chains. I recommend sticking the first 2 bolts due the fall potential doing the opening boulder problem.

Burly start with poor feet--I used a stick clip for this one. Gets easier the higher you go. 

 As one might expect from a route with only 3 bolts, its bouldery. I found myself executing some pretty funky sequences.
content.protection: Three bolts and anchors with biners in 'em for speedy lowering.
content.location: Starts just as the roof section of Undead cats area peters out. Left of the juggy and popular unfinished monkey business. Starts on the same sandy rock island/ledge thing as that route as well.

content.description: Shares a bolt with A Thousand Meows from Beyond the Grave.
content.location: Far left on Undead Cats wall.

content.description: No commentÂ

Route to the right of Nac Nac. leftmost route with glues in bolts. Starts on flake, goes up then veers left. Great moves the whole way, with two amazing bouldery cruxes, with thank you god clip stance at top. Giant fun roof at top with crimp rails!!! So much traxion.
content.protection: 6 glue in bolts, two top anchors with chains and carabiner

climbs.name: A Thousand Meows from Beyond the Grave

content.description: Shares a bolt with Dead Cats Do Meow.
content.location: Far left of Undead Cats between Life in the Cat's Lane and Dead Cats Do Meow.

content.description:
This wall offers good concentration of quality mid to upper 11s and a handful of 12s, but only one route lower than 11 and that is a 10d. Warm ups can be found to the right at Bee Wall or Cheech and Chong Wall. Alternative warm up can also be found a little farther down to the right on Buzzard's Roof and Little Guides Wall. 

  Also, it should be noted, this wall bears no resemblance to Dead Cats, but was designated as the place to make fun of route names at Reimer's Proper, hence the name "Undead Cats Wall"
